Here are the manual steps to create the same EKS cluster that your Terraform file provisions:

Step 1 — Create VPC

AWS Console → VPC → Create VPC
  Name:       eks-vpc
  IPv4 CIDR:  10.0.0.0/16
  DNS hostnames: Enable  ✅
  DNS resolution: Enable ✅

Step 2 — Create Subnets (2 AZs)

VPC → Subnets → Create Subnet

Subnet 1:
  VPC:               eks-vpc
  Name:              eks-public-subnet-1
  AZ:                us-east-2a
  CIDR:              10.0.1.0/24
  Auto-assign IP:    Enable ✅

Subnet 2:
  VPC:               eks-vpc
  Name:              eks-public-subnet-2
  AZ:                us-east-2b
  CIDR:              10.0.2.0/24
  Auto-assign IP:    Enable ✅

Step 3 — Create Internet Gateway

VPC → Internet Gateways → Create
  Name: eks-igw

→ Actions → Attach to VPC → select eks-vpc

Step 4 — Create Route Table

VPC → Route Tables → Create
  Name: eks-route-table
  VPC:  eks-vpc

→ Routes tab → Edit routes → Add route
  Destination: 0.0.0.0/0
  Target:      eks-igw  (Internet Gateway)

→ Subnet Associations → Edit
  Associate: eks-public-subnet-1 ✅
  Associate: eks-public-subnet-2 ✅

Step 5 — Create IAM Role for EKS Cluster

IAM → Roles → Create Role
  Trusted entity:  AWS Service
  Use case:        EKS → EKS Cluster
  
  Name: eks-cluster-role

Attach policy:
  ✅ AmazonEKSClusterPolicy

Step 6 — Create IAM Role for Node Group

IAM → Roles → Create Role
  Trusted entity:  AWS Service
  Use case:        EC2

  Name: eks-node-role

Attach these 3 policies:
  ✅ AmazonEKSWorkerNodePolicy
  ✅ AmazonEKS_CNI_Policy
  ✅ AmazonEC2ContainerRegistryReadOnly

Step 7 — Create EKS Cluster

EKS → Clusters → Create Cluster

  Name:     my-eks-cluster
  Version:  latest (1.29 or above)
  Role:     eks-cluster-role

→ Networking:
  VPC:      eks-vpc
  Subnets:  eks-public-subnet-1
            eks-public-subnet-2
  Security group: default or create new

→ Cluster endpoint access: Public ✅

→ Click Create  (takes ~10 minutes)

Step 8 — Create Node Group

EKS → Clusters → my-eks-cluster
→ Compute tab → Add Node Group

  Name:          my-node-group
  Node IAM role: eks-node-role

→ Next — Compute config:
  AMI type:       Amazon Linux 2
  Instance type:  t3.micro
  Disk size:      20 GB

→ Next — Scaling config:
  Desired: 2
  Minimum: 1
  Maximum: 3

→ Next — Networking:
  Subnets: eks-public-subnet-1
           eks-public-subnet-2

→ Create  (takes ~5 minutes)

Step 9 — Connect kubectl to Cluster

# Install AWS CLI + kubectl first

# Update kubeconfig
aws eks update-kubeconfig \
  --region us-east-2 \
  --name my-eks-cluster

# Verify connection
kubectl get nodes

# Expected output:
NAME                STATUS   ROLES    AGE
ip-10-0-1-xx...    Ready    <none>   2m
ip-10-0-2-xx...    Ready    <none>   2m

Step 10 — Verify Everything

kubectl get nodes          # should show 2 nodes
kubectl get pods -A        # system pods running
kubectl cluster-info       # shows cluster endpoint

Terraform vs Manual — What Each Step Maps To

| Terraform Resource            | Manual Step                   |
| ----------------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| aws_vpc                       | Step 1 — Create VPC           |
| aws_subnet x2                 | Step 2 — Create 2 subnets     |
| aws_internet_gateway          | Step 3 — Create IGW           |
| aws_route_table               | Step 4 — Create route table   |
| aws_iam_role eks_cluster_role | Step 5 — IAM role for cluster |
| aws_iam_role eks_node_role    | Step 6 — IAM role for nodes   |
| aws_eks_cluster               | Step 7 — Create EKS cluster   |
| aws_eks_node_group            | Step 8 — Create node group    |
| outputs                       | Step 9 — kubectl cluster-info |

























































